result.execSummary:
Jenny Roberta Williams was extradited to another county, state or jurisdiction. Extradition means Jenny Roberta Williams was accused or convicted of an offense in another county, state or jurisdiction and was taken there to face their charge(s) or conviction.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.descr: Records of prosec. are converted data. See file.

records.addlTxt: Called 10:53 am. Jenny Williams appears in custody and without attorney. Charles Simono appears for the State of Wisconsin. The defendant waives right to interpreter (deaf). Defendant sits next to court reporter and reads along with "real time". The court advises of waiver and consent to extradition. Williams signs waiver and consents to extradition. Court signs and makes defendant aware that MN will be coming to pick her up. Defendant requests to be transferred to MN ASAP through writing. Several written notes in file by the defendant.
